Description
Write a story covering all the characteristics mentioned in the attached ﬁle.
Once you have written the ﬁrst draft exchange work with a classmates, make corrections to eachothers work.
Make the corrections.
Be prepared to read your story next class.
The features of the story that you should write are these:
1. 180-200 words
2. 5 paragraphs: Introduction; three main paragraphs with the succession of the events; conclusion.
3. Use of all the past tenses seen in class (you can include any other tense if you need but the past tenses
are mandatory:
a. past simple;
b. past progressive; Was/ Were + ing
c. past perfect; Had + participle
i. “The past perfect shows the earlier action and the past simple shows the later action.”
d. present perfect; have or has + past participle
i. past actions or states which are still connected to the present.
e. used to.
4. Use of the following resources: linking words; several adjectives to describe places, characters and
situations; direct speech.
5. Use of the phrases provided in the list below. (Useful language).
6. Tell the story in ﬁrst or third person.
7. The topic is totally free.
1
Stories are characterised by:
● the use of past tenses (/t was raining when! set out. |put on my raincoat, opened the door and went
outside. When |reached the bus stop, |realised|hadn’t locked the front door.)
● linking words/phrases that show time and sequence of events (ﬁrst/at ﬁrst, then/next, after/before that,
during, while, meanwhile, as soon as, at that moment, by the time, in the end/ﬁnally etc).
● descriptive adjectives/adverbs to make the story more interesting (elegant, pleasant, breathtaking, fast,
etc).
● direct speech to make the story more dramatic (“Please help me!” she begged.)
Star ting a story/Setting the scene
● … felt (tired) as she had been (working on her computer all morning).
● It was (snowing heavily) when … (woke up that day).
Leading up to the main event
● At ﬁrst, we didn't notice …
● The (party) hadonly just (started) when ...
● The next thing (Ann) knew, (she was …).
The main event/climax of the story
● They started (shouting desperately).
● I felt sure (the car) was going to (crash).
Describing people/places/feelings
● The young man near the door …
● We walked down … Street trying to .
● To their (surprise/disgust/horror etc) … ,
● Imagine our (disappointment) when …
Ending astory
● I've never felt so (relieved/scared/ embarrassed etc) in my whole life.
● We knew they would never … again.
● It was the most (embarrassing/exciting/ amazing) moment I've ever experienced.
